   Ä About the Game ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
   race256 is a simple track or race style game for one player written in 256
   bytes.  the game was designed for a small coding competition between
   various people on the internet, to see who could code the funnest game in
   only 256 or less bytes.  the game could possibly be described as a
   spinoff of outrun, but much simpler as you can see.


   Ä How to Play ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ
   the object of the game is to score as many points as possible.  you gain
   points as you move along the track.  if your vehicle (marked by the single
   pixel near the bottom) moves off the track, you die.

   the controls are simple.  use your left and right arrow keys to move your
   car, spacecraft, raft, or whatever you can imagine it is, left and right.
   to quit the game, simply cause death by running off the track.

   when you die, you will return to dos/textmode and your score will be
   printed in the upper left corner.


   Ä Notes on Design ÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄÄ

     ù code size is 239 bytes
     ù the track data is thirteen bytes long, one byte per track section
     ù the game seems to run flicker-free without any retrace waits
     ù a 386 is required
     ù a VGA is required
     ù due to size limits the following are non-existent:
        - 386 checking
        - VGA checking
        - Random track generator
        - Ability to "jump" gaps in the track
        - Color fading from front to back of the track
        - Larger, more defined vehicle :)
       I wanted to add all of these and more (of course) but this was simply
       impossible due to the target size I needed.


